descript.abstract: U.S. Populated Place Areas represents populated place areas within United States identified by the U.S. Bureau of the Census.
descript.purpose: U.S. Populated Place Areas provides areal locations for populated places identified by the U.S. Bureau of the Census including attributes city name, FIPS code, Census class, and selected demographic data.
descript.supplinf: Largest scale when displaying the data: 1:100,000.

enttyp.enttypd: The polygons represent concentrations of population either legally bounded as incorporated places, or identified by the U.S. Census Bureau as census designated places.

attrdomv.udom: Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.

attr.attrdef: The class of the populated place.

edom.edomvd: In Connecticut, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania, an incorporated place.

Census designated place - A statistical entity, defined for each decennial census according to Census Bureau guidelines, comprising a densely settled concentration of population that is not within an incorporated place, but is locally identified by a name.

A type of incorporated place in 49 States and the District of Columbia. In 20 States, some or all cities are not part of any minor civil division, and the Census Bureau also treats these as county subdivisions, statistically equivalent to minor civil divisions.
A type of incorporated place in 30 States. In New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and South Dakota, the Census Bureau treats these towns as the equivalent of a minor civil division.
A type of incorporated place in 20 States. The Census Bureau treats all villages in New Jersey, South Dakota, and Wisconsin, and some villages in Ohio as county subdivisions.

procstep.procdesc: The data included in these boundary files was extracted from the 1990 Census Version TIGER/Line files (CD-ROM edition). The County, Tract, Block Group, and Place files have been edited together. This means that where appropriate, they nest on top of one another. For example, a segment of a place boundary that happens to be along a county border will match exactly with the corresponding segment in the County Boundary File.

horizpa.horizpar: The geospatial part of this data set was extracted from the 1990 Census Version TIGER/Line™ files (CD–ROM edition). The positional accuracy of the TIGER/Line coordinates varies with the source materials used but at best meets the established National Map Accuracy standards (+/- 167 feet approximately) where 1:100,000-scale maps from the USGS are the source. The Census Bureau cannot specify the accuracy of feature updates added by its field staff or of features derived from the GBF/DIME-Files or other map sources. Thus, the level of positional accuracy in the TIGER/Line files is not suitable for high-precision measurement applications such as engineering problems, property transfers, or other uses that might require highly accurate measurements of the earth's surface.
